pull_request.title: Fix: Foreign Currency Account API Validation for Special Characters
pull_request.body:
## Problem
Foreign currency account API endpoints were rejecting account IDs with special characters (like `49146/61094`) due to incorrect validation that expected MongoDB ObjectIds instead of account numbers.

## Root Cause
The API routes were using `isMongoId()` validation for account parameters, but foreign currency account numbers from israeli-bank-scrapers contain slash characters and are not MongoDB ObjectIds.

## Solution
Updated three foreign currency API endpoints to use proper account number validation:

### Changes Made
- **GET `/api/foreign-currency/accounts/:accountNumber`** - Changed from `:id` to `:accountNumber` parameter
- **GET `/api/foreign-currency/accounts/:accountNumber/transactions`** - Updated parameter validation
- **PUT `/api/foreign-currency/accounts/:accountNumber/balance`** - Updated parameter validation

### Technical Details
- Changed validation from `isMongoId()` to `isLength({ min: 1, max: 50 })`
- Added URL decoding for account numbers to handle encoded special characters
- Updated database queries to find by `accountNumber` field instead of `_id`
- Maintained internal MongoDB ObjectId usage for transaction lookups

## Testing
- ✅ Verified backend validation accepts account numbers with slashes
- ✅ Confirmed foreign currency extraction logic is correctly implemented
- ✅ Investment transactions integration verified working properly

## Impact
- Fixes API integration for israeli-bank-scrapers foreign currency accounts
- Enables proper handling of account numbers with special characters
- No breaking changes to existing functionality

## Related Issues
Resolves backend validation errors preventing foreign currency account API calls from frontend.

pull_request.title: Fix: Foreign Currency Account API Validation for Special Characters
pull_request.body:
## Problem
Foreign currency account API endpoints were rejecting account IDs with special characters (like `49146/61094`) due to incorrect validation that expected MongoDB ObjectIds instead of account numbers.

## Root Cause
The API routes were using `isMongoId()` validation for account parameters, but foreign currency account numbers from israeli-bank-scrapers contain slash characters and are not MongoDB ObjectIds.

## Solution
Updated three foreign currency API endpoints to use proper account number validation:

### Changes Made
- **GET `/api/foreign-currency/accounts/:accountNumber`** - Changed from `:id` to `:accountNumber` parameter
- **GET `/api/foreign-currency/accounts/:accountNumber/transactions`** - Updated parameter validation
- **PUT `/api/foreign-currency/accounts/:accountNumber/balance`** - Updated parameter validation

### Technical Details
- Changed validation from `isMongoId()` to `isLength({ min: 1, max: 50 })`
- Added URL decoding for account numbers to handle encoded special characters
- Updated database queries to find by `accountNumber` field instead of `_id`
- Maintained internal MongoDB ObjectId usage for transaction lookups

## Testing
- ✅ Verified backend validation accepts account numbers with slashes
- ✅ Confirmed foreign currency extraction logic is correctly implemented
- ✅ Investment transactions integration verified working properly

## Impact
- Fixes API integration for israeli-bank-scrapers foreign currency accounts
- Enables proper handling of account numbers with special characters
- No breaking changes to existing functionality

## Related Issues
Resolves backend validation errors preventing foreign currency account API calls from frontend.

issue.title: Remaining credits
issue.body: ### Feature Description ### Feature Request: Usage Tracker / Credit Consumption Indicator **Summary** Add a **usage tracker** under the chat interface (similar to Cursor IDE) to display how much of the user’s included credits/usage have been consumed, and how much remains. --- **Why this is useful** - Gives users **immediate awareness** of their consumption without needing to navigate to account/billing pages. - Helps prevent **unexpected overages** by warning users when they’re approaching their limit. - Improves the **UX for budgeting** monthly usage, especially for developers working in bursts. --- **Example from Cursor** Here’s how Cursor displays this feature: It shows: - Current spend vs total included usage (e.g., `$15.93 / $20 included usage`) - A progress bar visualizing percentage of credits consumed - Reset date for the next billing cycle - A warning banner when usage passes a certain threshold (e.g., *80% used*) --- **Proposed Implementation in Kiro** - Display usage info below the chat input area. - Elements to include: - **Current usage vs included limit** (e.g., `$X / $Y`, or credits remaining) - **Progress bar** - **Reset date** (e.g., “Resets Sep 6, 2025”) - **Optional warning message** when usage crosses thresholds (e.g., 80%, 95%). --- **Impact** - Improves **transparency**. - Reduces **support load** from billing/usage inquiries. - Enhances **trust** and **user satisfaction**. --- **Priority**: Medium – improves UX significantly but does not block core functionality. ### Use Case would use this feature to monitor my credit/usage directly while working inside Kiro, without needing to leave the IDE or log into my billing dashboard. For example: When running many AI-assisted completions in one session, I can keep track of how much of my monthly allowance is left. If I see I’m nearing my limit (e.g., 80%), I can consciously adjust my usage and avoid hitting a hard stop unexpectedly. This is especially helpful during deadlines or long coding sessions when I can’t afford interruptions. This makes Kiro feel more transparent, user-friendly, and predictable. ### Additional Context Additional Context Cursor IDE already has a similar usage tracker that appears below the chat input. It shows: Current spend vs total allowance (e.g., $15.93 / $20) A progress bar visualizing percentage used Reset date for the billing cycle Warning messages at thresholds (80%, 95%) Here’s a screenshot from Cursor for reference: This type of UI would be a lightweight but very impactful improvement to the Kiro experience.

issue.title: Waking laptop with power button immediately puts it in suspend again
issue.body:
Howdy,

When running niri, after suspending my laptop (due to idle or explicitly calling `systemctl suspend`), if I press the power button, it will briefly wake up (for < 1 second) before going back into suspend. It seems that niri must be registering the power button event (that woke the laptop up) and immediately putting the laptop back to sleep again.

A viable workaround is setting `disable-power-key-handling` in the niri config file. This prevents this bug, but it also means that the power button no longer works for putting the laptop to sleep.

This occurs with the default config.

* niri version: niri 25.05.1 (8ba57fc)

Whenever I change something in the params panel, after the reload, the panel breaks. You can see that the background changes and I can't use the inputs. Whatever I click it thinks I want to resize it. ### Screenshots https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/bbeb631d-3905-4e52-b6e3-3eabe839a98e ### Version numbers Please complete the following information: * Lookbook: 2.3.12 * ViewComponent: 4.0.1 * Rails: 8.0.2 * Ruby: 3.4 ### Additional context I'm using this layout file ```erb "> Component Preview <%= yield :head %> <%= stylesheet_link_tag 'ui', data: { turbo_track: 'reload' } %>
"> <%= yield %>
```

comment.body:
Thanks for the kind words @adrianthedev - not quite at the Avo level but I'm glad you like it  :)

I've taken a look at this and annoyingly I can't seem to reproduce the issue in the video in either Chrome or Safari.

I've got a couple of questions to help me try to figure out why this is happening, if you have the time:

1. Do you run into the same problem on the hosted Lookbook demo app? The [button playground example](https://demo.lookbook.build/lookbook/inspect/elements/button/playground) has a number of params you can edit to test.
2. Do you also have the same issue on a viewport wide enough to give you the 'full' layout (i.e. with the sidebar on the left) or is it only on the mobile layout shown in the video?
3. Does clearing cookies and localstorage for the domain you are running the Lookbook instance on make any difference?
4. Is this happening on param panels for all components? Are there any with a different combination of fields that don't show this behaviour?
5. Could you try opening Lookbook in a browser window without any browser extensions enabled and see if that makes any difference? Incognito mode might get you there, depending on your setup.
The last one (i.e. blaming your browser extensions 😂) seems unlikely to be the cause because you are seeing it in both Chrome and Safari. But because I can't seem to recreate it and I spotted the line "Injected CSS loaded successfully" in your console it made me wonder if it might be something be some JS/CSS being injected into the page that is clashing somehow.

Also the layout file you posted looks fine, I can't see anything in there that would cause any issues.

In the meantime I'll have a bit more of a play and try to see if I can recreate it at all here - if I come up with anything I'll let you know.

issue.body:
Hi Sharanya,

Thank you for releasing the code and resources for HalluShift. I found the work very insightful and valuable for studying hallucination detection.

I noticed that in Table II of the paper, HalluShift is compared against several baseline methods (e.g., SelfCheckGPT etc.). I found that for some of these methods there are no repo or code. Could you kindly share the code (or scripts/instructions) for reproducing these baseline methods? 

This would greatly help in reproducing the evaluation pipeline as described in the paper and running a fair comparison across all methods on new datasets. If the code cannot be shared directly, even references to the specific implementations you used (e.g., repos, configurations, or adaptations) would be very helpful.

Thank you again for your excellent work and for making HalluShift available to the community!

Best regards,
Xinyan

comment.body:
Hi Xinyan,  

I appreciate your interest in **HalluShift**. We’re glad you found the work useful.  

Regarding your query on the baseline methods (e.g., SelfCheckGPT, etc.) in *Table II*:  
We did not re-implement these methods ourselves. Instead, we directly reported the baseline results from the [*Halloscope* NeurIPS paper](https://proceedings.neurips.cc/paper_files/paper/2024/file/ba92705991cfbbcedc26e27e833ebbae-Paper-Conference.pdf), and maintained the same configuration as theirs for comparison.

For reproducing the baselines, we recommend referring to the *Halloscope* paper and its supplementary materials for implementation details and configurations. 

Best regards,  
Sharanya

commits.message:
Switch to builtin gettext implementation

Handle translation from PO to MO files in `build.rs`.

Parse MO files at build time and generate source code containing the
localization mappings.

Replace runtime dependency on gettext by custom handling of language selection,
and using compile-time generated maps for localization.

Choose which languages to embed localization data for via cargo features.
Disable most gettext code aside from stubs to keep the code working when no
languages are enabled.

Advantages of this approach:
- We have no runtime dependency on gettext anymore.
- The implementation has the same behavior everywhere.
- Our implementation is significantly simpler than GNU gettext.
- We can have localization in cargo-only builds by embedding localizations into
  the code.
  Previously, localization in such builds only worked as long as the binary was
  not moved from the build directory.
- Generating the MO files from `build.rs` removes the need for scripting it in
  several places (cmake, checks).
- MO file generation, parsing, and embedding happens automatically when building
  fish, eliminating the need to run anything aside from rebuilding fish.
- Reduced overhead when disabling localization, both for compilation time and
  binary size. At the moment, a release build with all features disabled results
  in a binary size of 4.6 MB, whereas when enabling only the
  `localize-all-languages` feature, the resulting size is 9.5 MB.

Disadvantages of this approach:
- Our own runtime implementation of gettext needs to be maintained.
- The implementation has a more limited feature set (but I don't think it lacks
  any features which have been in use by fish).

Add gettext localization test

This test requires certain locales, so it might not run in most circumstances.
In CI, we can generate the locales we need, so at least there the test should
run without issues.

Build gettext maps in separate crate

This is a build performance optimization. Building all localization maps takes
about 1.5 seconds on my machine. Incurring this cost every time fish is built
unnecessarily slows down builds and increases storage demands. By generating the
maps in a separate crate, we can rebuild that crate only when necessary, i.e.
when code in that crate changed, or something in the `po` directory was
modified. For regular development, this means that after the initial build, the
build-time cost of including pre-built maps is negligible unless PO files are
changed.

The only downside of this approach compared to the previous implementation I see
is that when a language is added or removed, in addition to the PO file, now two
other locations need to be updated instead of one (`Cargo.toml` of both the
workspace root and the crate responsible for building the mappings).
